    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-11-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-11-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="400"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d400">
                <head>400. Memorandum for the Record by the Secretary of State<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d400fn1">Source: Eisenhower Library, Dulles Papers,
                        Meetings with the President.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-11-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 15, 1957</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>At the Cabinet meeting this morning I spoke briefly to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> with reference to the subject matter
                    of his memorandum to me of November 13, 1957, annexed,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d400fn2">
                        <ref target="#d398">Document 398</ref>.</note> dealing with <persName
                        corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName>. I said that we were giving this
                    matter closest consideration. At the present time we had good relations with all
                    the Arab States from Morocco to Saudi Arabia, excluding Egypt and Syria. We did
                    not want in an effort to win good relations with <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1"
                        >Nasser</persName> to alienate those who had maintained good relations with
                    us. There was danger that <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName> would
                    be satisfied with nothing less than our willingness to treat with him as the
                    leader of the Arab world; that was the position he coveted. But for us to accede
                    to this would antagonize King <persName corresp="#p_SAA1">Saud</persName> and
                    the other Arab countries such as Jordan, Lebanon, Iraq, and so forth, which
                    looked primarily to <persName corresp="#p_SAA1">Saud</persName> and were
                    somewhat fearful of <persName corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName>.</p>
                <p>The President felt that we could not of course be disloyal to King <persName
                        corresp="#p_SAA1">Saud</persName> or attempt to push <persName
                        corresp="#p_NNNGA1">Nasser</persName> into leadership ahead of <persName
                        corresp="#p_SAA1">Saud</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="strong">JFD</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
